#1 Sigmoid cancer
This disease was diagnosed in January 2010 and so far has not yet been treated.  The primary lesion in the sigmoid is biopsy-proven.  Imaging with a CT-scan shows a-1.6-cm lesion in the liver.  This is most likely a metastasis, although obviously not proven.  I discussed with Dr. Raymond the different approaches to his condition.  He understands that there is a strong likelihood that he has metastatic disease, although this is not proven.  One possible approach would be to schedule a surgical procedure to remove the primary tumor and during that procedure address the liver lesion.  The liver lesion could be removed along with the primary tumor.  Dr. Raymond understands that adjuvant therapy is indicated in any case.  This would consist of the combination of FOLFOX with or without Avastin.  We discussed the potential benefits and side-effects of such chemotherapy including nausea, vomiting, weakness, alopecia, diarrhea, peripheral neuropathy, cold intolerance, and loss of taste as well as immune suppression.  We discussed at length whether it would be necessary to obtain a biopsy and/or a PET scan prior to a procedure.  I told him that it would probably be feasible to address the liver lesion during the time of surgery.  I have scheduled him with Drs. Robinson from Colorectal Surgery and Jone from Liver Surgery on Monday to further assess the situation.  I also explained to him that adjuvant therapy could be started no earlier than four weeks after surgery.
#2 Question of inflammatory bowel disease
Dr. Heron symptoms as well as the  findings on the CT-scan certainly are consistent with inflammatory bowel disease.  However, biopsies of the affected part of the colon did not reveal any conclusive results.  The presence of IBD, however, would certainly help to explain Dr. Raymond's early-onset of this disease.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, not on file at Huggins Clinic.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

