[start section id="20103"]

Dr. Raymond is a 47-year-old obstetrician from Loretto, Minnesota, who over the past three years experienced diarrhea.  Additionally, over the past two-to-three months he experienced pain in both of his testicles.  He has occasional hematochezia and has lost 20 pounds over the past year.  He states that this was intentional.  Medical workup here at the Lake Center included a colonoscopy on January 21, 2010, that was a suboptimal prep and only 25% of the mucosa could be visualized.  Beyond that there was melanosis coli in the right colon.  Beginning at the splenic flexure, the mucosa had an edematous boggy appearance according to the operative report.  Twenty to twenty-five cm from the anal verge a large polypoid lesion was encountered.  Biopsy of this lesion revealed adenocarcinoma.  Immunohistochemistry for microsatellite instability was performed, and no abnormalities were found.  A CT-scan on January 28, 2010, showed marked circumferential thickening of the distal colonic wall from the splenic flexure to the anus with inflammation and edema in the pericolonic fat and rectosigmoid mesentery.  There are fluid collections in the sigmoid mesentery as well as adenopathy that may be reactive or metastatic.  Also, a-1.6-cm hypodense mass in the posterolateral aspect of the right hepatic lobe in segment six can be seen.  A CEA was 32.4.
Dr. Raymond now comes to Saint Anthonys County Memorial Hospital to discuss further diagnostic workup and treatment.

[end section id="20103"]

